6. Prompt Engineering Techniques
==================================================

Zero-Shot Prompting

Write a follow-up email to a client after a meeting.

--------------------------------------------------

One-Shot Prompting

Write a follow-up email to a client after a meeting.

Example:

Dear [Client Name],

Thank you for meeting with me today.

I appreciate the opportunity to discuss our project.

Please let me know if you have any further questions.

Best regards,
[Your Name]

--------------------------------------------------

Few-Shot (Multi-Shot) Prompting

Write a follow-up email to a client after a meeting.

Example 1

Dear [Client Name],

Thank you for meeting with me today.

I appreciate the opportunity to discuss our project.

Please let me know if you have any further questions.

Best regards,
[Your Name]

Example 2

Hi [Client Name],

It was great meeting with you today.

I look forward to working together on this project.

If you have any questions, feel free to reach out.

Best,
[Your Name]

--------------------------------------------------

Role Prompting

Act as a sales representative.

Write a follow-up email to a client after a meeting.

--------------------------------------------------

Tabular Format Prompting

Summarize the key points from the meeting.

Create a table with columns:
- Topic
- Discussion
- Action Items

--------------------------------------------------

Ask Before Answering

Before writing the follow-up email, ask me for any specific details you need about the meeting.

--------------------------------------------------

Fill in the Blank Prompting

Dear __________,

Thank you for meeting with me today.

I appreciate the opportunity to discuss __________.

Please let me know if you have any further questions.

Best regards,

____________

--------------------------------------------------

Perspective Prompting

Write a follow-up email after a meeting from the perspective of a project manager.

--------------------------------------------------

Chain of Thought Prompting

First, thank the client for the meeting.

Then summarize the key discussion points.

Finally, offer additional assistance and provide your contact information.

